{{Lunisolar December}} '''Lunisolar December''' (旧暦十二月) is the twelfth month of the {{ill|Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|ja|旧暦|1=Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|1=Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|11=Japanese Lunisolar Calendar}} used in {{ill|China|ja|中国}} and {{ill|Japan|ja|日本}}, based on the {{ill|Lunisolar calendar|ja|太陰太陽暦|1=Lunisolar calendar|2=ja|3=太陰太陽暦|comment=note that this is not the Japanese lunisolar calendar it is any lunisolar calendar|4=ru|5=Лунно-солнечный календарь|6=de|7=Lunisolarkalender|8=es|9=Calendario lunisolar|10=fr|11=Calendrier luni-solaire}}.
In calendars such as the {{ill|Japanese Calendar|ja|和暦}} prior to the {{ill|Tenpō Calendar|ja|天保暦}}, December is defined as the month that includes {{ill|Great Cold|ja|大寒}}. In the {{ill|Gregorian Calendar|1=Gregorian calendar|2=ja|3=グレゴリオ暦|4=fr|5=Calendrier grégorien|6=de|7=Gregorianischer Kalender|8=tl|9=Kalendaryong Gregoryano|10=ru|11=Григорианский календарь|ja|グレゴリオ暦}}, it corresponds approximately to late {{ill|December|ja|12月}} to early {{ill|February|ja|2月}}. In the Eastern {{ill|Lunisolar calendar|ja|太陰太陽暦|1=Lunisolar calendar|2=ja|3=太陰太陽暦|comment=note that this is not the Japanese lunisolar calendar it is any lunisolar calendar|4=ru|5=Лунно-солнечный календарь|6=de|7=Lunisolarkalender|8=es|9=Calendario lunisolar|10=fr|11=Calendrier luni-solaire}}, because the number of days in a month, known as {{ill|Large and Small|ja|大小}} (with large months having 30 days and small months 29 days), varies by year, there are years when the final day of the month is the 29th.
== Alternate Names and Aliases == ;Etymology of “Shiwasu” December’s alternate name is '''Shiwasu''' (しはす, しわす). The origin of “shiwasu” is unknown due to its antiquity. The {{ill|Daigenkai|ja|大言海}} states, “It is said to be an abbreviation of ‘Toshihatsu’ (トシハツ), or that it signifies a month in which all matters come to fruition (シハ), as well as the time when agricultural activities conclude,” and also remarks, “The names of the twelve months are assigned according to the progression of the ripening of rice” (see the {{ill|Mutsuki|ja|睦月}} entry). Furthermore, there is a theory from the Heian period that attributes the term to the busy movement of monks (with “shi” meaning monk) attending Buddhist ceremonies, as mentioned in {{ill|Shokuyojijirishu|ja|色葉字類抄}}; however, this is regarded as a folk etymology lacking linguistic basis, and by the Heian period the true origin of “shiwasu” had already been lost. {{Sfn|Sanseido|2015}}<ref>高島俊男：お言葉ですが・・・（７）、漢字語源の筋ちがい、p.86、文春文庫、第1刷、2006th year 6月10日、（株）文藝春秋</ref> (see also {{ill|Folk Etymology|ja|民間語源#日本語における民間語源}}).
